TT 1865 "AMICIA HAS BEEN DETECTED" GAME__ALERT_AMICIA
TT 1866 "HUGO HAS BEEN DETECTED" GAME__ALERT_HUGO
TT 1867 "HUGO HAS BEEN CAUGHT" GAME__CAPTURE_HUGO
TT 1868 "Hugo's Herbarium" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1
TT 1869 "Description of the category" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_DESC
TT 1870 "Daisy" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_1
TT 1871 "The daisy is a symbol of innocence and purity, and probably owes its fame to the whiteness of its petals. It was used in infusions with calming and digestive properties, known to also promote scar healing. Daisy petals were also used in salads and popular among both nobles and commoners, due to their slight pepper flavor." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_1_DESC
TT 1872 "Carnations" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_2
TT 1873 "It is referred to as the “flower of God” in some languages. Some attribute its nickname to its beauty, others to legends that it was born from the blood of Christ's stigmata or the Virgin Mary's tears. It has thus become a symbol of love, passion, and commitment. Its petals seemingly amplify sweating when used to treat fevers, and vinegar was produced from it to clean buboes, contributing to its reputation." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_2_DESC
TT 1874 "Aquilegia" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_3
TT 1875 "Named for “aquila”, the Latin word for eagle, in reference to the shape of its talon-like petals. Ancolia is a symbol of sadness and troubled souls—even of madness. While its flowers are sweet and edible, its roots and stems are highly toxic. When digested, they cause the entire digestive system to become inflamed and can lead to dangerous palpitations." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_3_DESC
TT 1876 "Gladiolus" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_4
TT 1877 "Found in both tended gardens and wild fields, many of its variants are poisonous, but one of them was consumed in dishes and used in remedies. The shape of its leaves, reminiscent of a Gladius sword, made it the flower of heroes and gladiators in the Roman era: a symbol of strength and vigor." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_4_DESC
TT 1878 "Hawthorn" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_5
TT 1879 "A thorny bush used to mark out the borders of gardens and properties, hawthorn has become a symbol of cautious hope. It is the subject of many legends, the most prestigious of which depicts it as Christ's crown of thorns. When ingested as an infusion, it regulates the heartbeat and combats shortness of breath." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_5_DESC
TT 1880 "St. John's wort" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_6
TT 1881 "Also called “Saint John's herb”, it is a symbol of animosity, but also one of protection and light, St. John's wort is considered a remedy to melancholy and other mental afflictions. Despite its nickname, “devil hunter,” ingesting it can still significantly disrupt the heart rate, causing arrhythmia and tachycardia." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_6_DESC
TT 1882 "Lavender" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_7
TT 1883 "Lavender is widely known for its perfume, and for its colour among weavers. The well-educated also use it in many cataplasms for its purifying values. It was rubbed on viper bites to weaken the venom, or on children's scalps to fight lice. Over time, it has become a symbol of dedication and loyalty." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_7_DESC
TT 1884 "Rhododendron" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_8
TT 1885 "While the rhododendron is harmless, honey made from its flowers is said to carry toxins with hallucinogenic and laxative properties. This is what seemingly thwarted the Greek army resulting in the Retreat of the Ten Thousand—the soldiers gorged themselves on this honey after looting and suffered its effects. Its apparent harmfulness is probably what made it a symbol of risk and danger." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_8_DESC
TT 1886 "Cinquefoils" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_9
TT 1887 "It owes its name to its number of petals—five, like the fingers on a hand. From a medicinal point of view, it was used from Antiquity in the form of pastes or decoctions to fight illnesses of the digestive tract, calm fever, and stop bleeding. It is also an important symbol in heraldry, decorating the coats of arms of the great families of north-west France." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_9_DESC
TT 1888 "Daffodil" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_10
TT 1889 "It is said that it grew from the remains of Narcissus, a mythological figure who died while looking at his own reflection. It symbolizes egoism and selfishness. Despite a marked toxic potential recognized by humanity since Antiquity, many European countries have used it to treat tumors, epilepsy, and hair loss—to varying degrees of success." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_10_DESC
TT 1890 "Black Nightshade" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_11
TT 1891 "A symbol of truth, associated by some with demonic witchcraft, the black nightshade has many worrisome nicknames: “devil's herb”, “death cherries”, and “beautiful death”. The toxicity of its berries is certainly a factor; consuming them can lead to death." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_11_DESC
TT 1892 "Rockfoils" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_12
TT 1893 "Saxifrage, also known as “stone-breaker”, is often found in cold, mountainous environments, seeping into rock crevices to avoid the frost. It symbolizes inevitability and a form of despair. This nickname comes from the fact that it was considered a means of dissolving kidney stones." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_12_DESC
TT 1894 "Christmas rose" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_13
TT 1895 "Used since Antiquity to treat dementia and some forms of paralysis, the plant quickly became a symbol of anxiety and disquiet—this is likely due to its toxicity, as handling it with one's bare hands causes violent irritations and even more severe reactions if ingested. Strangely enough, it is found in nativity scenes around Christmas. It was supposedly born from the tears of Madelon, a young shepherdess who was desperate to offer a gift to the newborn Christ." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_1_ITEM_13_DESC
TT 1896 "Hugo's collection" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2
TT 1897 "Arrowhead" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_1
TT 1898 "This tiny, white star is a colony-forming aquatic wildflower often found in shallow lakes, and castle moats. Its genus name, “sagitta”, means “arrow” in Latin and comes from the shape of its leaves. It's also known as “Duck potato” as it produces corms, which are usually eaten stewed. It is said to absorb large amounts of heavy metallic elements such as copper or lead, two of the seven “pure metals” in alchemy." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_1_DESC
TT 1899 "Chamomile" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_2
TT 1900 "In the wild, it looks like tiny daisy heads, dotting the fields with blossoms of white and yellow. Traditionally, herbalists recommend it as a powerful sleep aid. Its protective properties are also supposed to cast out spells and its flowers are often associated with luck and financial success: many gamblers used to wash their hands in tea made from it to attract money." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_2_DESC
TT 1901 "Gentian" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_3
TT 1902 "According to Pliny the Elder, it gets its name from Gentius, last king of Illyria, who experienced its special healing effects when using it to clean wounds. Originating in the Alps, the roots of some species are turned into a sweet and sour liqueur, drunk as an appetiser for its purgative and bracing effects. Queen of the mountains, its bright, deep colour clearly relates to sorrow and pain. Offering a bouquet of Gentians will express your contempt." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_3_DESC
TT 1903 "Anemone" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_4
TT 1904 "Thriving on the shores of the Mediterranean, “Anemôné” in Greek means “daughter of the wind”. Also named Windflower, it blooms in heavy weather, then sows its feathery seeds across great distances. In Greek mythology, it is linked to abandonment and said to be born from the tears shed by the goddess Aphrodite when grieving Adonis' death. Peasants' beliefs tell that Amenone closing up is the sign of an impending rain." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_4_DESC
TT 1905 "Carnation" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_5
TT 1906 "The origins of the “flower of the gods” may reach back to antiquity. The Greeks used to offer “corone” (flower garlands) at coronation ceremonies and the Romans rewarded athletes with “Jupiter's Flowers” for outstanding performances. In Christian legends, Marie's tears turned into pink carnations as she was mourning her son and “carnis” would refer to the flesh of the Christ. Their bouquets, symbols of purity and gratitude, once honoured the love of a mother." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_5_DESC
TT 1907 "Jay" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_6
TT 1908 "Sentinel of the woods, its loud call warns all the creatures around when predators approach. Legend tells that it was once falsely accused by the other birds, and every one of them was sentenced to grant it one feather. Maybe that's why it's considered as the emblem of light, with its colourful, bright plumage, illuminating even the darkest places. If you find its feather, it will bring you the energy to heal and never give up." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_6_DESC
TT 1909 "Black headed gull" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_7
TT 1910 "Sociable and noisy, it usually flocks in open shorelines and dunes. It is of great significance to seamen and the shipwrecked out at sea: those who hear its call will sight land and be back home soon. In folktales, it symbolises maternal bonding. Dreaming of a gull is sign of a painful goodbye to the mother, while finding a feather from one would mean freedom and emancipation from the family." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_7_DESC
TT 1911 "Black kite" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_8
TT 1912 "As a scavenger, it is a fascinating yet misunderstood bird of prey with a low, strident call, and a graceful silhouette gliding in circles above lakes. In Greek mythology, it is associated with Apollo—the sun god—and embodies the gift of awareness and foresight. The kite's meaning is acceptance of the past and moving forward. If its feather pops up, you will soon experience a drastic change in your life." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_8_DESC
TT 1913 "Barn owl" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_9
TT 1914 "Ghostly pale with dark eyes, the white lady haunts abandoned barns or hollow logs and is commonly associated with prophecy and wisdom. Owning its feather connects you to your inner skills and gives the strength to take action in your life, while following your intuition. Crossing the path of this nocturnal hunter will also remind you that the world—even if dark and brutal—can still be filled with wonders." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_9_DESC
TT 1915 "Raven" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_10
TT 1916 "Since historical times, superstition associates it with bad omens and witchery, partly because of its disturbing, iridescent plumage but also because it makes a feast from any cadavers it comes across. ~A raven visiting in a dream is the symbol of self-transmutation: this spirit guide helps discover powers lying in the dark of our mind. Its feather brings the strength to overcome great changes and the promise of someone watching over us on life's challenging journey." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_10_DESC
TT 1917 "European goldfinch" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_11
TT 1918 "With its lovely song and brilliant lemon colour, this charming fellow must have gotten lost in the caves, as it usually lives on floodplains. It will visit your backyard if only you offer thistle seeds to peck—one of its common names is also 'thistle-finch'. In religious traditions, it symbolizes resurrection and liveliness while old pagan beliefs even thought it could bring a powerful protection against the scourge of the plague." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_11_DESC
TT 1919 "Greylag goose" GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_12
TT 1920 "This ancestor of our farmyard goose can be found in many European wetlands. Long ago, in Rome, sacred geese of the temple of Juno used to warn of attacks as they were said to sense danger. In popular folklore, it also symbolises the call for adventure and journeys to legendary places. Its feathers, traditionally favoured for writing with, will remind you that you should follow your family and never forget your roots." GAME__CODEX_CATEGORY_2_ITEM_12_DESC
